Bulk fields with general brane kinetic terms 

F. del Aguila,
M. Perez-Victoria and
J. Santiago

  Departamento de Fisica Teorica y del Cosmos and
Centro Andaluz de Fisica de Particulas Elementales (CAFPE),
Universidad de Granada, E-18071 Granada, Spain

  Dipartimento di Fisica "G. Galilei", Universita di
Padova and INFN, Sezione di Padova, Via Marzolo 8, I-35131 Padua,
Italy 

  Institute for Particle Physics Phenomenology, University
of Durham, South Road, Durham DH1 3LE, UK

 


Abstract 



We analyse the effect of general brane kinetic terms for bulk scalars,
fermions and gauge bosons in theories with extra dimensions, with and
without supersymmetry. We find in particular a singular behaviour when
these terms contain derivatives orthogonal to the 
brane. This is brought about by  divergences arising at
second and higher order in perturbation theory. We argue that
this behaviour can be smoothed down by classical renormalization.
 





Introduction 

Field theoretical models with extra dimensions typically include one
or more lower dimensional defects on which some fields can be
localized. These defects ("branes" from now on) can have different
microscopic realizations: D-branes, domain walls, cosmic strings,
orbifold fixed points, . 
In general, the fields propagating in
all the dimensions (bulk fields) couple 
to fields propagating on the
branes . Moreover, 
it is possible that the action includes terms localized on the branes
involving only bulk fields ("brane terms", for short). 
They may have important consequences. 
A crucial observation is that brane terms are
induced by radiative corrections. This is allowed as Poincare
invariance is broken by the branes. Quantum divergences localized on
the branes can appear in the correlators of
bulk fields when the bulk fields are coupled to fields living
on them . Furthermore, in orbifolds this can
occur even in the absence of brane couplings at tree
level . In any case, it is
clear that the presence of divergent radiative 
corrections localized on the branes requires the introduction of
divergent brane counterterms. Therefore, the corresponding brane
couplings run with the renormalization scale, and cannot be set to
zero at all scales. Furthermore, this indicates that they should be
considered free parameters of the theory and be included at
tree level (see  for a detailed argument). Of
course, since
interacting theories in higher dimensions are nonrenormalizable, 
these considerations are only meaningful in the framework of
effective field theory, and it is important to take into account
possible suppressions of the brane couplings by inverse powers of the
cutoff scale . 

Brane terms are always suppressed by , ,
with respect to the analogous bulk terms. Therefore one would
expect that their effect on observables should be a small perturbation
of the corresponding results without brane terms. In this article we
show that, contrary to this expectation, certain brane operators
modify severely some observables-like Kaluza-Klein (KK)
masses-even when their coefficients are 
very small. This breakdown of perturbation theory has to do with the
interplay between the thin brane limit and the limit of large
, in which the coefficients of the brane operators approach
zero. Unless otherwise stated, we will always
consider infinitely thin, delta-function branes, although we will
often make use of thick branes as intermediate regulators.
On the other hand, the underlying fundamental
theory is usually assumed to be smooth in its parameters, so that all
its low energy predictions should be perturbatively calculable using
some effective theory. From this point of view, the relevant question
is how to incorporate in a low energy effective description a
mechanism to make the expansion in  well defined. Here we
sketch a possible answer in the spirit of perturbative renormalization
theory. 

We shall concentrate on brane kinetic terms. Kinetic terms localized
on a brane were first invoked 
by Dvali, Gabadadze and Porrati  to recover 4D 
gravitational behaviour at short distances in infinite extra
dimensions. The same 
mechanism was subsequently applied in  to gauge
theories. In , the one loop 
radiative corrections to brane terms and their first order impact on
KK spectra were calculated in different 
theories. In , a detailed computation of
infinite and finite radiative 
corrections to bulk and brane kinetic terms of gauge fields (with and
without Hosotani mechanism) was performed.  
The phenomenology of gauge fields in compact dimensions with
(tree-level) brane kinetic terms has been discussed recently
in  (flat space)
and  (warped 
space). A particular fermionic case has been addressed
in . Finally, brane kinetic terms in
supersymmetric models have been studied
in .
In all these works, brane kinetic terms 
are found to have a significant impact on model building and
phenomenology. And, as observed above, they must be generically
included for consistency. 

Here we analyse at the classical level the effect of all the possible
 brane kinetic terms for scalar, fermion and
gauge 
fields. In particular we examine brane terms containing derivatives 
with respect to the coordinates orthogonal to the brane. These terms
have not been studied in detail before(Except
in , where the singular terms were
"massaged" via a 
classical renormalization. We compare this approach with ours in
Section .) . We find that they give rise to
solutions to the 
equations of motion which 
exhibit a rather singular behaviour: they decouple
from the brane and become insensitive to the magnitude of all brane
couplings; furthermore, physical observables for arbitrarily small
coefficients of these terms do not approach the ones for 
vanishing coefficients. This is related to the appearance of
 singularities at second and higher orders in the
 expansion. These singularities are a common feature of
field theoretical models with infinitely thin
branes . We also study brane
kinetic terms in supersymmetric theories and find that supersymmetry
requires the presence of higher order kinetic terms in the on-shell
action. These terms improve but do not cure the singular
behaviour of the classical fields. More generally, any
effective theory will contain higher order terms which may
significantly change the solutions derived from the first order
Lagrangian. One can then hope that these terms
be such that the exact solutions are smooth in all
the parameters of the theory. We will discuss this possibility below. 
Although most of our considerations apply to general
field theories in extra dimensions, for definiteness
we study here theories defined on a flat 5D space with
the 5th dimension compatified on an  orbifold. Moreover, in
order to keep the discussion and calculations as simple as possible,
we neglect masses and consider kinetic terms localized on 
only one of the fixed points (even if kinetic terms on both branes are
natural and lead to interesting phenomenology ). 

The structure of the paper is as follows. In Section  we
perform the exact KK reduction of the free action for particles of
spin  in the presence of general brane kinetic terms.
In Section  we study the supersymmetric case. In
Section  we examine in detail an example elucidating the
role of thin brane singularities. In Section  we
argue that classical renormalization makes the theory smooth and
perturbation theory well defined. This is also interpreted as the
restriction to a subclass of effective theories with particular
reductions of couplings. We summarize and discuss our results in
Section . Finally, we collect in
Appendix  the general first order results, and
give an example of renormalization in Appendix . 



Exact KK reduction 

In this section we study the exact (, nonperturbative) KK reduction
of the most general free action with leading order brane terms for
massless scalars, gauge bosons and fermions propagating in 
. We consider fields which are functions of the
coordinates ,  of  and 
, of , and which are eigenstates of , ,
even or odd functions of . For simplicity, we only include
brane terms at the fixed point . 

Some of the operators we consider are products of two odd
factors times a delta function. These terms are sometimes argued to
vanish on parity grounds. However, these arguments are no longer valid
when the (derivatives of) wave functions appearing in these terms
develop discontinuities across the
branes . Deriving and 
solving the equations of motion when the action contains this sort of
terms is tricky , and the same applies to 
brane terms containing derivatives with respect to . 

In order to
treat all these cases rigorously we regularize the branes using
several (smooth) representations of the delta function, of width 
. We perform all the 
calculations with these resolved branes, and only take the thin brane
limit  at the very end. Furthermore, we employ
different representations in order to check that our results are
regularization independent. In some cases we have resorted to
numerical methods to 
solve the relevant differential equations. Still, it is possible to
see that the numerical solutions converge rapidly in 
the thin brane limit to certain functions, which we take as our
analytical solutions. The reader can find an explicit analytical
calculation in the simple case discussed in Section .


